= Schleicher and the <span style="color: #385A38;">Agrarians</span>

Schleicher’s economic and agricultural ministers remain locked in a bitter struggle over tariffs—part of the broader conflict between industrialists and agrarians. Schleicher has refused to take a side, maintaining a façade of unity for the public. However, his failure to uphold a promise to continue Papen’s protectionist policies—meant to shield German farm products from cheap foreign imports—has led the increasingly right-wing National Rural League (RLB) to turn against him.

President Hindenburg, like many conservative Germans of his generation, viewed agriculture as the bedrock of national life—a source of tradition and moral strength. It was he who, of his own accord, summoned the economic and agricultural ministers, along with Schleicher, to a meeting with the RLB. The cabinet temporarily mollified the situation by promising future action.

Yet Hindenburg and the RLB remained dissatisfied, particularly over the government’s failure to renew a decree shielding bankrupt farmers from foreclosure. In truth, however, the RLB had long since become a political instrument of the <span style="color: #7A3C00;">**NSDAP**</span>, more interested in toppling Schleicher than securing concessions. Despite the earlier agreement, they publicly attacked the chancellor—prompting an angry Schleicher to break off further talks. Hindenburg, under the influence of his *Junker* friends, voiced his disapproval.

Eventually, Schleicher relented and agreed to issue a new measure protecting bankrupt farmers from foreclosure.

